Product Requirements Document (PRD)
🧭 Product Name

rottyctl (CLI)
rotty (Web UI)

1. 🎯 Objective

Provide a lightweight, scalable tool to:

Discover and scan storage (NAS + object storage)
Identify ROT (Redundant, Obsolete, Trivial) data
Quantify cost impact
Recommend tiering or deletion actions
2. 👤 Target Users
DevOps / Platform Engineers
Storage & Infrastructure teams
FinOps / Cloud cost teams
3. 🧱 Core Features
3.1 Scanner Engine
Functional Requirements
Support:
S3-compatible storage
Azure Blob (via Microsoft Azure)
NAS (NFS / SMB mounts)
Collect metadata:
path
size
last modified
last accessed (if available)
Handle:
billions of objects (streaming, not in-memory)
Non-Functional
Parallel scanning (configurable concurrency)
Resume interrupted scans
Incremental scan support (delta mode)
3.2 ROT Classification Engine
Rules (configurable)
Redundant:
duplicate files (size + hash optional)
Obsolete:
last modified > X days
Trivial:
size < threshold OR temp/log patterns
Output

Tagged dataset:

file → {rot_type: obsolete, risk: low}
3.3 Cost Simulation Engine
Inputs
Storage provider pricing
Data size per class
Output
Current cost
Projected cost (after tiering)
Savings:
monthly
annual
Providers (initial)
AWS S3
Azure Blob
Generic (user-defined)
Include:
storage cost per GB
retrieval cost
early deletion penalties
3.4 Tiering Recommendation Engine
Actions
Move to:
cold storage
archive tiers
external vaults (e.g. Veeam Vault)
Delete (optional)
Output Example
/logs/2021 → Archive (low risk, 2y unused)
/tmp       → Delete (trivial)
/finance   → Keep (high risk)
3.5 CLI Interface (Primary)
Example Commands
rotctl scan s3://bucket
rotctl analyze ./scan.json --older-than 90d
rotctl simulate --tier azure-archive
rotctl report --format table
Requirements
Fast startup
Pipe-friendly (JSON output)
Works offline after scan
3.6 Web UI (Secondary but Important)
Purpose
Visual exploration
Multi-share management
Reporting for stakeholders
Features
Dashboard:
total storage
ROT %
potential savings
Filters:
age
size
storage class
Drill-down:
by bucket/share/path
Architecture
Backend API (Go)
Frontend (React or similar)
4. ⚙️ System Architecture
High-Level Components
[Scanner Workers] → [Metadata Stream] → [Analyzer Engine]
                                      → [Cost Engine]
                                      → [Storage DB]
                                              ↓
                                   [CLI + Web UI]
Storage Layer

Options:

SQLite (local runs)
PostgreSQL (multi-user / UI mode)
Scaling Strategy (THIS IS CRITICAL)
1. Streaming, not batch
Never load full dataset into memory
Process as a pipeline
2. Worker Pool Model
Concurrent scanners:
per bucket
per prefix

Tunable:

--workers 32
3. Use existing tools (smart reuse)

Instead of reinventing scanning:

Integrate with rclone
Use lsjson
Or library mode

👉 This alone saves weeks of work.

4. Partitioning Strategy

For large datasets:

Prefix-based scanning:

s3://bucket/a*
s3://bucket/b*
Time-based partitioning
5. Incremental Mode (huge win)

Store:

last scan timestamp

Next run:

only scan changed objects
5. 📊 Performance Requirements
Handle:
100M+ objects
100+ TB datasets
Throughput:
≥ 10k objects/sec (target baseline)
Memory:
O(1) relative to dataset size (streaming)
6. 🔐 Security & Access
Read-only scanning by default
No data modification unless explicitly enabled
Credentials:
env vars
config file
IAM roles
7. 🧪 Observability
Logs:
scan progress
errors
Metrics:
files scanned/sec
bytes processed
Optional:
Prometheus endpoint
8. 🧩 Extensibility

Plugin-style design for:

storage backends
cost models
classification rules
9. 🚀 MVP Scope (build THIS first)

If you want to avoid overbuilding:

Phase 1 (CLI only)
Scan (via rclone or SDK)
Age-based ROT detection
Simple cost calculator
JSON + table output
Phase 2
Tiering simulation
Configurable rules
Phase 3
Web UI
Multi-scan aggregation
⚖️ Key Design Decisions (important)
1. CLI-first is correct
Easier adoption
Scriptable
DevOps-friendly
2. Web UI should NOT block MVP
Add after core engine is solid
3. Efficiency comes from:
streaming
concurrency
reusing tools like rclone
💥 Final thought

The real success of this tool won’t be:

“it scans fast”

It’ll be:

“it tells me exactly how much money I’m wasting and what to do about it”
